InfoWorld news	http://www.infoworld.com/cgi-bin/redirect?source=rss&url=http://www.infoworld.com/article/08/02/01/codegear-russia_1.html	CodeGear to supply 1 million dev tool licenses to Russia	none	Sci/Tech	<div class="rxbodyfield"><p class="ArticleBody" page="1">In a major boost for CodeGear's development tools, the company has been awarded a contract by the Russian Federal Agency of Education to provide 1 million seat licenses of its Delphi and C++Builder products.</p><p align="right"><a href="http://ad.doubleclick.net/jump/idg.us.info.rss/news;pos=imu;tile=6;sz=336x280;skey=patch_management;pkey=security;ord=123456789?" target="_blank" /><img src="http://ad.doubleclick.net/ad/idg.us.info.rss/news;pos=imu;tile=6;sz=336x280;skey=patch_management;pkey=security;ord=123456789?" width="336" height="280" border="0" alt="" align="right"/></a></p><p class="ArticleBody" page="1">CodeGear's software will be used as part of the Russian government's strategy to bolster computer science and IT education in an economy that has been driven by oil and gas exploration, said CodeGear CEO Jim Douglas. U.S. and Russian software vendors are creating a software bundle to be distributed at universities and secondary schools throughout Russia, he said. The arrangement also features software from other vendors, such as Corel, Douglas said. "For us, it's one of the largest deals that we've done in [the] Europe, Middle East, Africa region as a company," Douglas said.</p><p class="ArticleBody" page="1">The entire deal is part of a Russian federal initiative called the National State Project of High-Grade Education. The total value of the deal is worth $100 million, but CodeGear would not say what its share of that pie will be.</p><p class="ArticleBody" page="1">Both Delphi and Delphi for .Net will be provided along with C++Builder. The total number of licenses distributed for the three products will reach 1 million.</p><p class="ArticleBody" page="1">Delphi is focused on native, compiled Windows application development on the desktop. Asked if the deal represents a revival for Delphi, which had been a Borland Software product, Douglas acknowledged that this might be the perception. "From our perspective, [Delphi has] never been diminished," he said.</p><p class="ArticleBody" page="1">While Microsoft is pushing enterprise-level application development, sectors like engineering and science seek native, compiled applications, Douglas said. "This [deal] is just a continued indicator of Delphi in that segment," he said. CodeGear with the deal is focusing on client-server desktop applications.</p><p class="ArticleBody" page="1">CodeGear, Douglas said, does not compete much with Microsoft's Visual Studio platform anymore. Microsoft's focus is on .Net and managed code, while CodeGear is centered on the native compiled space, although it does have .Net capabilities.</p><p class="ArticleBody" page="1">CodeGear's offering in the managed code space is its JBuilder product for Java application development in the enterprise, Douglas said.</p><p class="ArticleBody" page="1">CodeGear, meanwhile, is making product plans for the year that include adding Unicode capabilities for internationalization to Delphi and C++Builder. This will be included in the 2008 versions of the products due out in the first half of this year.</p><p class="ArticleBody" page="1">Also planned are language enhancements for Delphi and a second release of CodeGear's Delphi for PHP, which will identified as version 1.1 and be more robust, Douglas said.</p><p class="ArticleBody" page="1">CodeGear was spun out of Borland about a year ago to focus on development tools. But CodeGear still is owned by Borland, which now concentrates on the application lifecycle management space. Plans still call for CodeGear to become a separate, independent company.</p></div>	4	2008-02-01 12:20:20	\N

InfoWorld news	http://www.infoworld.com/cgi-bin/redirect?source=rss&url=http://www.infoworld.com/article/08/02/01/Flash-price-drop-spurring-innovation_1.html	Flash price drop spurring innovation	none	Sci/Tech	<div class="rxbodyfield"><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">A massive decline in the price of NAND flash memory, the chips that store photos in digital cameras and music in iPods, is prompting innovation among companies trying to increase sales.</p><p align="right"><a href="http://ad.doubleclick.net/jump/idg.us.info.rss/news;pos=imu;tile=6;sz=336x280;skey=patch_management;pkey=security;ord=123456789?" target="_blank" /><img src="http://ad.doubleclick.net/ad/idg.us.info.rss/news;pos=imu;tile=6;sz=336x280;skey=patch_management;pkey=security;ord=123456789?" width="336" height="280" border="0" alt="" align="right"/></a></p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">A few of the items users are likely to see more widespread in gadgets this year include greatly expanded storage capacity in SD (secure digital) cards, USB (universal serial bus) flash sticks and internal storage, as well as new, lower-cost SSDs (solid-state discs) in notebook computers.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">The price of mainstream 4Gb SLC (single-level cell) NAND flash memory chips has fallen 73 percent since mid-August to $4.96 late Thursday, according to DRAMeXchange Technology, which runs an <a href="http://www.dramexchange.com/">online clearinghouse</a> for the chips. The chips hit a high of $18.50 on Aug. 14. The price of 4Gb MLC (multi-level cell) NAND flash chips have taken a slightly worse dive, 75 percent down to $2.23 on Thursday, compared to its summer high of $8.85 per chip.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">The difference between SLC and MLC is cost and life span. SLC normally costs about three times more than MLC, and has a lifetime of 100,000 write cycles. MLC has a lifetime of only 10,000 write cycles.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">Toshiba and Samsung have both developed new 128GB SSDs based in MLC NAND to expand their use in notebook PCs. The new SSDs are less expensive, giving notebook PC designers more choices in storage.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">&quot;At 128G bytes, you&#39;re giving consumers the kind of storage space they expect in a notebook,&quot; said Jim Elliott, director of flash marketing at Samsung, in an interview.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">To work around the lifespan issue, Toshiba and Samsung use controller chips to spread writes across the drive to avoid wearing out any one portion too quickly.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">The new MLC-based drives are an important step forward for SSDs in the battle against hard disk drives (HDD). At 128GB, an SSD stands are far better chance of replacing an HDD in laptop computers because it removes some of the high-capacity advantage HDDs hold.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">SSDs have several advantages over HDDs; they&#39;re lighter, more rugged, consume less power, make no noise and enable a computer to start up and load software faster than HDDs. But SSDs are a lot more expensive than HDDs, which is why they&#39;re mainly used in the business laptop market, where users are willing to pay more for performance and reliability.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">Elliott believes SSDs for PCs will account for 27 percent of NAND consumption by 2011, particularly in business laptops and mobile devices.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">SanDisk has taken a slightly different route in SSDs than Toshiba and Samsung. The company made a 72GB SSD in a thinner form factor aimed at mobile devices. The drive takes up less space, so it could be used in a range of mobile devices, said Iri Trashanski, director of strategic business development at SanDisk.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">He doesn&#39;t believe there will be a market for 128GB SSDs for a while.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">Brian Kumagi, senior business development manager NAND flash memory business at Toshiba, believes the lower cost of MLC NAND chips will play a major role in seeing 128GB SSDs gain market share.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">Toshiba is also offering MLC NAND SSDs in 32GB and 64GB capacities to entice laptop PC makers and makers of digital music players and other devices requiring more storage.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">There are several other products where companies are adding NAND flash to increase storage capacity and improve devices. One, thanks to the iPhone, is handsets, said Elliott.</p><p page="2" class="ArticleBody">Multimedia handsets will likely see 8GB of embedded flash memory become the standard this year, and card slots are being added to a host of mobile phones to increase storage and for added content delivery, including movies, games, software and more.</p><p page="2" class="ArticleBody">Plus, low prices are encouraging new innovation, just as low NAND prices helped put the chips into more iPods earlier this decade. One area is in video cameras, namely, <a href="http://www.theflip.com/">Flip</a> video and similar devices.</p><p page="2" class="ArticleBody">For $119.99, users can buy a Flip video camcorder that uses NAND flash memory to store 30 minutes of recordings.</p><p page="2" class="ArticleBody">In addition, devices such as GPS (global positioning system) for cars will need more flash when 3D (three dimensional) digital maps start replacing 2D maps.</p><p page="2" class="ArticleBody">The good news for users is that there are so many NAND flash memory makers in the world today that prices will remain low or at least reasonable for a long time.</p><p page="2" class="ArticleBody">In a report titled &quot;Flash to crash,&quot; Macquarie Securities chip analyst Warren Lau wrote that NAND flash memory prices will likely remain low throughout the first half of this year, with little room for upside until the third quarter.</p><p page="2" class="ArticleBody">&quot;We continue to warn that NAND flash will see excess supply in the first half of 2008 owing to aggressive production ramp (at IM Flash and Toshiba) and the seasonally weaker period for consumer products (digital still cameras, handsets and MP3),&quot; he wrote.</p><p page="2" class="ArticleBody">Much of the possible price movements in NAND flash actually depend on Apple because of the widespread popularity of the iPod and iPhone.</p><p page="2" class="ArticleBody">The company announced it has already shipped over 4 million iPhones and continues to ramp shipments. iPod shipment growth has dropped a bit, according to market researcher Gartner, but higher capacity iPod products such as the Touch have done well in the market.</p><p page="2" class="ArticleBody">&quot;Apple is a critical driver of NAND flash consumption and will continue to yield great influence on NAND flash vendors,&quot; Gartner said in a report on Monday.</p></div>	4	2008-02-01 13:27:33	\N
InfoWorld news	http://www.infoworld.com/cgi-bin/redirect?source=rss&url=http://www.infoworld.com/article/08/02/01/05FE-news-quiz_1.html	Answer key: You don't know tech	none	Sci/Tech	<div class="rxbodyfield"><p class="ArticleBody" page="1">Now that you know how you scored, you probably want to know why. Check out the answers below for the gory details. And be sure to return next year for another news quiz, ripped straight from the tech headlines.</p><p align="right"><a href="http://ad.doubleclick.net/jump/idg.us.info.rss/news;pos=imu;tile=6;sz=336x280;skey=patch_management;pkey=security;ord=123456789?" target="_blank" /><img src="http://ad.doubleclick.net/ad/idg.us.info.rss/news;pos=imu;tile=6;sz=336x280;skey=patch_management;pkey=security;ord=123456789?" width="336" height="280" border="0" alt="" align="right"/></a></p><p class="ArticleBody" page="1"><b>Question 1:</b> Why is Microsoft still under the court's watchful eye?</p><p class="ArticleBody" page="1">10 points<br/>\
<i>c. Microsoft's delays in filing technical documents</i></p><p class="ArticleBody" page="1">It could be worse. <a href="http://www.businessweek.com/ap/financialnews/D8UFT6RO0.htm" class="regularArticleU">Judge Colleen Kollar-Kotelly turned down a request</a> from 10 state attorneys general to extend oversight through 2012. Redmond still faces two anti-trust probes in Europe, where unlike in the U.S., <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2007/06/10/business/10microsoft.html?_r=1&amp;hp&amp;oref=slogin" class="regularArticleU">its former attorneys are not members of the organization</a> tasked to oversee it.</p><p class="ArticleBody" page="1"><b>Question 2:</b> Who's tired of filling the trough for IPS, telcos, and device makers?</p><p class="ArticleBody" page="1">10 points<br/>\
<i>a. U2 band manager Paul McGuinness</i></p><p class="ArticleBody" page="1"><a href="http://blog.wired.com/music/2008/01/u2-manager-want.html" class="regularArticleU">McGuinesses' comments</a>, made to attendees of a music industry trade show in Cannes, France, echoed the drumbeat struck by the <a href="http://www.theregister.co.uk/2008/01/27/ifpi_digital_threat/" class="regularArticleU">International Federation of the Phonographic Industry last week</a>. Having failed to stop users from swapping files, the record industry is going after the pipes used to transport them. Expect to hear this tune in high rotation over the coming months, even if you can't dance to it.</p><p class="ArticleBody" page="1"><b>Question 3:</b> What happened to those missing iPhones?</p><p class="ArticleBody" page="1">10 points<br/>\
<i>d.</i> <i>We don't know nothin' about no missing iPhones</i></p><p class="ArticleBody" page="1">5 points<br/>\
<i>b.</i> <i>They fell off a truck and got unlocked</i></p><p class="ArticleBody" page="1">At least, d is the answer Apple and AT&amp;T are offering, after <a href="http://www.infoworld.com/article/08/01/25/Apple-missing-iPhones_1.html" class="regularArticleU">analysts pored over figures released by the two companies</a>. Apple says it sold 3.75 million iPhones last year, AT&amp;T activated roughly 2 million, and about 350K were sold in Europe, leaving 1.4 million unaccounted for. Give yourself 5 points for answering b, since it's believed the gadget's popularity has created <a href="http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2008/01/29/where-are-those-million-iphones-everywhere/index.html?ex=1359349200&amp;#38;en=55236179ed714948&amp;%2338;ei=5088&amp;%2338;partner=rssnyt&amp;%2338;emc=rss" class="regularArticleU">a robust international market for hacked iPhones</a> that can be used with any carrier.</p><p class="ArticleBody" page="1"><b>Question 4:</b> What caused the Mideast and India to lose Internet access?</p><p class="ArticleBody" page="1">10 points<br/>\
<i>c.</i> <i>A whale chewed through the undersea cables</i></p><p class="ArticleBody" page="1">OK, maybe it wasn't a whale. But <a href="http://www.infoworld.com/article/08/01/31/Cut-cable-disrupts-Internet-in-Middle-East_1.html" class="regularArticleU">something cut two undersea cables</a> that delivered bandwidth to a half dozen countries, causing havoc for some firms using India-based call centers. Officials say the break will take about two weeks to fix. So if you thought your PC maker's offshore support sucked already, you're in for a real treat.</p><p class="ArticleBody" page="1"><b>Question 5:</b> Whose personal loss record did SocGen's Jerome Kerviel break?</p><p class="ArticleBody" page="1">10 points<br/>\
<i>b. Brian Hunter at Amaranth Energy</i></p><p class="ArticleBody" page="1">Hunter managed to <a href="http://money.cnn.com/news/newsfeeds/articles/djhighlights/200801240656DOWJONESDJONLINE000597.htm" class="regularArticleU">lose only $6.6 billion speculating on natural gas</a> prices, ahead of Hamanaka ($2.6 billion), Leeson ($1.7 billion), and <a href="http://www.nzherald.co.nz/section/2/story.cfm?c_id=2&amp;objectid=10488853" class="regularArticleU">Iguchi ($1.1 billion)</a>. To set his record, Kerviel created fake e-mails with bogus trade requests and <a href="http://www.cio.com.au/index.php/id;1244340084;fp;2;fpid;1;pf;1" class="regularArticleU">hacked into SocGen's servers</a> to cover his activities. However, there's no indication Kerviel was on steroids at the time, so no need for an asterisk.</p><p class="ArticleBody" page="2"><b>Question 6:</b> How much coin did it take to snag the C block of analog spectrum?</p><p class="ArticleBody" page="2">10 points<br/>\
<i>a. $4,713,823,000</i></p><p class="ArticleBody" page="2">Only one bidder <a href="http://bits.blogs.nytimes.com/2008/01/31/spectrum-auction-the-c-block-bidding-is-over-at-47-billion/?ref=technology" class="regularArticleU">exceeded the FCC's reserve price of $4.6 billion</a> on the auction's final day. But the identity of that bidder will remain a mystery until all 1,100 pieces of spectrum at auction have been sold, a process that could take months. The smart money is on either Verizon Wireless or Google, but no one knows for sure. Remember the presidential election in 2000? The FCC is the new Florida.</p><p class="ArticleBody" page="2"><b>Question 7:</b> What's holding up Apple's new online rental service?</p><p class="ArticleBody" page="2">10 points<br/>\
<i>c.</i> <i>The software isn't ready</i></p><p class="ArticleBody" page="2">Scheduled to be released by the end of January, Apple says <a href="http://www.macworld.com/article/131876/2008/01/appletv.html" class="regularArticleU">its Apple TV upgrade still isn't quite ready for prime time</a>, so it's holding off for a couple of weeks.</p><p class="ArticleBody" page="2"><b>Question 8:</b> What glitch is the MacBook Air NOT suffering?</p><p class="ArticleBody" page="2">10 points<br/>\
<i>d. Difficulty fitting the laptop inside nonstandard manila envelopes</i></p><p class="ArticleBody" page="2">Eagle-eyed MacWorld reporters noted <a href="http://www.macworld.com/article/131878/2008/01/macbookair.html" class="regularArticleU">several warnings about the MacBook Air's shortcomings</a> buried in the fine print at Apple.com. Interestingly, some of the documents cited in the story vanished into thin air after their presence was revealed. No word yet whether Apple plans to sue itself for leaking insider information.</p><p class="ArticleBody" page="2"><b>Question 9:</b> How did Yahoo celebrate its better-than-expected financial results?</p><p class="ArticleBody" page="2">10 points<br/>\
<i>d.</i> <i>All of the above</i></p><p class="ArticleBody" page="2">Though making $200 million is better than losing it, Yahoo's profits were down 23 percent from the previous year, <a href="http://www.infoworld.com/article/08/01/29/Yahoos-Q4-sales-up-profit-down_1.html" class="regularArticleU">causing it to lay off 7 percent of its workforce</a>. Yahoo renewed a partnership with AT&amp;T, though likely at much less favorable terms. CEO Jerry Yang predicted Yahoo would be facing ?headwinds? throughout the rest of the year, reigniting <a href="http://svextra.com/blogs/gmsv/2008/01/no_sir_they_werent_cheering_the_layoff_news_--_they_were_yelling_yah_who.html" class="regularArticleU">rumors of a possible takeover</a> by AT&amp;T, Microsoft, or one of the media giants.</p><p class="ArticleBody" page="2"><b>Question 10:</b> What's HTC phones plus ABC fines divided by Dell kiosks?</p><p class="ArticleBody" page="2">10 points<br/>\
<i>a. 24,286</i></p><p class="ArticleBody" page="2">HTC says it sold approximately <a href="http://www.infoworld.com/article/08/01/22/HTC-sold-2-million-iPhone-rival-handsets_1.html" class="regularArticleU">2 million phones</a> last year via companies like Sprint and AT&amp;T. The FCC fined 52 ABC affiliates $1.4 million for <a href="http://www.rawstory.com/news/mochila/Bare_rear_could_cost_ABC_1_4_millio_01262008.html" class="regularArticleU">showing a woman's bare buttocks</a> in a 2003 episode of <i>NYPD Blue</i>. Dell is <a href="http://www.infoworld.com/article/08/01/30/Dell-shuts-140-retail-kiosks-in-US_1.html" class="regularArticleU">closing 140 retail kiosks</a> this year. So (2M + 1.4M)/140 = 24,286 (rounding up). Or, if you prefer, 12,143 per cheek. Be sure and tune in next week for another cheeky news quiz.</p><p class="ArticleBody" page="2">Ready for more? InfoWorld news	http://www.infoworld.com/cgi-bin/redirect?source=rss&url=http://www.infoworld.com/article/08/02/01/Microsoft-offers-to-buy-Yahoo-for-44-billion_1.html	Microsoft offers to buy Yahoo for $44.6 billion	none	Sci/Tech	<div class="rxbodyfield"><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">Microsoft has offered to buy Yahoo for around $44.6 billion in cash and shares, to better compete with Google in the market for online services.</p><p align="right"><a href="http://ad.doubleclick.net/jump/idg.us.info.rss/news;pos=imu;tile=6;sz=336x280;skey=patch_management;pkey=security;ord=123456789?" target="_blank" /><img src="http://ad.doubleclick.net/ad/idg.us.info.rss/news;pos=imu;tile=6;sz=336x280;skey=patch_management;pkey=security;ord=123456789?" width="336" height="280" border="0" alt="" align="right"/></a></p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">The market for online advertising is increasingly dominated by one player, Microsoft said, and merging with Yahoo will allow it to offer a competitive alternative.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">Microsoft expects the market for online advertising to almost double in size over the next three years, from $40 billion in 2007 to $80 billion by 2010. A merger will allow it to realize economies of scale and reduce capital costs as it addresses this market, it said.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">&quot;The combination of these two great teams would enable us to jointly deliver a broad range of new experiences to our customers that neither of us would have achieved on our own,&quot; said Ray Ozzie, chief software architect at Microsoft, in a statement.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">Microsoft expects to cut costs by $1 billion a year by realizing synergies with Yahoo in four areas: obtaining economies of scale as its audience increases; combining its research and development efforts with Yahoo&#39;s to innovate faster; eliminating operational redundancy to cut costs, and pooling expertise to innovate in video and mobile.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">The companies will work together to develop the merger plan, Microsoft said.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">It intends to pay key Yahoo engineers and other staff to stay following the merger.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">The offer represents a 62 percent premium over Yahoo&#39;s closing price on Thursday. Microsoft expects to receive all necessary approvals in the second half of this year.</p></div>	4	2008-02-01 14:44:22	\N
InfoWorld news	http://www.infoworld.com/cgi-bin/redirect?source=rss&url=http://www.infoworld.com/article/08/02/01/Micron-Intel-speed-up-flash-memory_1.html	Micron, Intel speed up flash memory	none	Sci/Tech	<div class="rxbodyfield"><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">Breaking the speed barrier of traditional flash memory, Intel and Micron Thursday announced a new flash memory architecture that increases the data transfer rates in consumer electronics by cutting the bottlenecks affecting conventional NAND flash memory.</p><p align="right"><a href="http://ad.doubleclick.net/jump/idg.us.info.rss/news;pos=imu;tile=6;sz=336x280;skey=patch_management;pkey=security;ord=123456789?" target="_blank" /><img src="http://ad.doubleclick.net/ad/idg.us.info.rss/news;pos=imu;tile=6;sz=336x280;skey=patch_management;pkey=security;ord=123456789?" width="336" height="280" border="0" alt="" align="right"/></a></p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">IM Flash Technologies, a joint venture between Intel and Micron, has developed an 8Gb SLC (single-level cell) high-speed NAND chip which can reach read speeds up to 200MBps and write speeds of up to 100MBps, which could mean faster data transfer between devices like solid-state drives and video cards.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">&quot;With the popularity of digital video cameras and video-on-demand services, high speed NAND can enable a high-definition movie to be transferred five times faster than conventional NAND,&quot; said Kirstin Bordner, a spokeswoman for Micron.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">Conventional NAND flash memory from Micron and other players currently transfer data at read rates of 40MBps, with write rates of about 20MBps.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">The speed improvements resulted from changes made to the NAND architecture and improvements in the read-write circuitry, Bordner said.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">This chip&#39;s architecture achieves the speed defined in the ONFI (Open NAND Flash Interface) 2.0 specification, according to Micron. Micron was one of the founders of the ONFI Working Group in 2006, and other member companies include Hynix Semiconductor, Intel, Phison Electronics, Sony and STMicroelectronics.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">Micron is now sampling the high-speed NAND component, with mass production expected to commence in the second half of 2008, the company said.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">Products based on the ONFI 2.0 specification have been under development and were expected, said Joseph Unsworth, a principal analyst at Gartner.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">&quot;It wasn&#39;t anything that wasn&#39;t expected. We knew that it was coming out,&quot; Unsworth said.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">The technology could see an immediate future for use in video and high-end photography devices that require flash memory with quick transfer speeds and reliable data retention, Unsworth said. However, it will be priced at a premium and only multimedia enthusiasts looking for high-performance flash memory would be willing buyers, Unsworth said.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">As prices stabilize, it will reach mainstream devices like MP3 players and digital cameras, but that could be a long time away, he said.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">The new flash technology from Micron and Intel could also face competition from Samsung and Toshiba, the world&#39;s top flash vendors, who combined represent 60 percent of products supplied in the NAND flash market. The two companies last year signed an agreement to share specifications to develop faster and more robust NAND interfaces, Unsworth said.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">While both factions will ultimately deliver high-performance flash technology to consumers, they need to unite under one banner to ease the development of high-speed flash technology. The market is split in half, and it needs one standard voice to simplify the development of flash memory for manufacturers, Unsworth said.</p></div>	4	2008-02-01 16:30:41	\N

InfoWorld news	http://www.infoworld.com/cgi-bin/redirect?source=rss&url=http://www.infoworld.com/article/08/02/01/Terry-Semel-quits-Yahoo-board_1.html	Terry Semel quits Yahoo board	none	Sci/Tech	<div class="rxbodyfield"><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">Terry Semel is stepping down as Yahoo&#39;s non-executive chairman, six months after handing over his CEO title to Jerry Yang.</p><p align="right"><a href="http://ad.doubleclick.net/jump/idg.us.info.rss/news;pos=imu;tile=6;sz=336x280;skey=patch_management;pkey=security;ord=123456789?" target="_blank" /><img src="http://ad.doubleclick.net/ad/idg.us.info.rss/news;pos=imu;tile=6;sz=336x280;skey=patch_management;pkey=security;ord=123456789?" width="336" height="280" border="0" alt="" align="right"/></a></p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">Semel is leaving the board effective immediately, Yahoo announced Thursday. He will be replaced as non-executive chairman by another board member, Roy Bostock, the company said.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">Semel was chairman and CEO of Yahoo for six years until he was replaced in a management shuffle last June. Yang, one of Yahoo&#39;s co-founders, was made CEO, and Semel was demoted to non-executive chairman.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">As CEO, Semel helped to build Yahoo&#39;s audience from 170 million to more than 500 million users. But he was also blamed for missteps that allowed Google to build a commanding lead in online search and advertising, prompting last year&#39;s reorganization.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">&quot;With the Company moving forward under new leadership, I believe this is an appropriate time for me to step down from the board,&quot; Semel said in the statement.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">He approached the board several months ago about leaving once a replacement could be found, Yahoo said.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">Bostock has a long history in the advertising industry, &quot;an area that is more important than ever to Yahoo&#39;s business and our long term success,&quot; the company said.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">On Tuesday&#160;<a href="http://www.infoworld.com/article/08/01/29/Yahoos-Q4-sales-up-profit-down_1.html">Yahoo reported that net income for its fourth quarter declined</a>&#160;to $206 million, from $269 million a year earlier. It also announced plans to lay off about 1,000 staff.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">Semel&#39;s departure from the board appears to mark the end of his tenure at Yahoo. Yang thanked him for &quot;his many contributions to Yahoo over the years&#160;-- and for helping to lay a firm foundation for future success and improved financial performance.&#8221;</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">Bostock has been a board member at Yahoo since May 2003 and was elected unanimously by the board to replace Semel. InfoWorld news	http://www.infoworld.com/cgi-bin/redirect?source=rss&url=http://www.infoworld.com/article/08/02/01/Microsoft-offer-to-Yahoo-board_1.html	Microsoft's offer to Yahoo's board	none	Sci/Tech	<div class="rxbodyfield"><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">In a letter to Yahoo&#39;s board, Microsoft CEO Steve Ballmer&#160;<a href="http://www.infoworld.com/article/08/02/01/Microsoft-offers-to-buy-Yahoo-for-44-billion_1.html">offered to acquire the company</a>&#160;for a per-share price of $31 in cash or 0.9509 of a share of Microsoft common stock -- a 62 percent premium above the Jan. 31, closing price of Yahoo -- and cited the broad range of ways in which the companies might work together to create a more effective competitor in the online marketplace. Below is the text of the letter that Microsoft sent to Yahoo&#39;s Board of Directors:</p><p align="right"><a href="http://ad.doubleclick.net/jump/idg.us.info.rss/news;pos=imu;tile=6;sz=336x280;skey=patch_management;pkey=security;ord=123456789?" target="_blank" /><img src="http://ad.doubleclick.net/ad/idg.us.info.rss/news;pos=imu;tile=6;sz=336x280;skey=patch_management;pkey=security;ord=123456789?" width="336" height="280" border="0" alt="" align="right"/></a></p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">January 31, 2008</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">Board of Directors</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">Yahoo! Inc.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">701 First Avenue</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">Sunnyvale, CA 94089</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">Attention: Roy Bostock, Chairman</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">Attention: Jerry Yang, Chief Executive Officer</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">Dear Members of the Board:</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">I am writing on behalf of the Board of Directors of Microsoft to make a proposal for a business combination of Microsoft and Yahoo!. Under our proposal, Microsoft would acquire all of the outstanding shares of Yahoo! common stock for per share consideration of $31 based on Microsoft&#39;s closing share price on January 31, 2008, payable in the form of $31 in cash or 0.9509 of a share of Microsoft common stock. Microsoft would provide each Yahoo! shareholder with the ability to choose whether to receive the consideration in cash or Microsoft common stock, subject to pro-ration so that in the aggregate one-half of the Yahoo! common shares will be exchanged for shares of Microsoft common stock and one-half of the Yahoo! common shares will be converted into the right to receive cash. Our proposal is not subject to any financing condition.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">Our proposal represents a 62% premium above the closing price of Yahoo! common stock of $19.18 on January 31, 2008. The implied premium for the operating assets of the company clearly is considerably greater when adjusted for the minority, non-controlled assets and cash. By whatever financial measure you use - EBITDA, free cash flow, operating cash flow, net income, or analyst target prices - this proposal represents a compelling value realization event for your shareholders.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">We believe that Microsoft common stock represents a very attractive investment opportunity for Yahoo!&#39;s shareholders. Microsoft has generated revenue growth of 15%, earnings growth of 26%, and a return on equity of 35% on average for the last three years. Microsoft&#39;s share price has generated shareholder returns of 8% during the last one year period and 28% during the last three year period, significantly outperforming the S&amp;P 500. It is our view that Microsoft has significant potential upside given the continued solid growth in our core businesses, the recent launch of Windows Vista, and other strategic initiatives.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">Microsoft&#39;s consistent belief has been that the combination of Microsoft and Yahoo! clearly represents the best way to deliver maximum value to our respective shareholders, as well as create a more efficient and competitive company that would provide greater value and service to our customers. In late 2006 and early 2007, we jointly explored a broad range of ways in which our two companies might work together. These discussions were based on a vision that the online businesses of Microsoft and Yahoo! should be aligned in some way to create a more effective competitor in the online marketplace. We discussed a number of alternatives ranging from commercial partnerships to a merger proposal, which you rejected. While a commercial partnership may have made sense at one time, Microsoft believes that the only alternative now is the combination of Microsoft and Yahoo! that we are proposing.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">In February 2007, I received a letter from your Chairman indicating the view of the Yahoo! Board that &quot;now is not the right time from the perspective of our shareholders to enter into discussions regarding an acquisition transaction.&quot; According to that letter, the principal reason for this view was the Yahoo! Board&#39;s confidence in the &quot;potential upside&quot; if management successfully executed on a reformulated strategy based on certain operational initiatives, such as Project Panama, and a significant organizational realignment. A year has gone by, and the competitive situation has not improved.</p><p page="2" class="ArticleBody">While online advertising growth continues, there are significant benefits of scale in advertising platform economics, in capital costs for search index build-out, and in research and development, making this a time of industry consolidation and convergence. Today, the market is increasingly dominated by one player who is consolidating its dominance through acquisition. Together, Microsoft and Yahoo! can offer a credible alternative for consumers, advertisers, and publishers. Synergies of this combination fall into four areas:</p><p page="2" class="ArticleBody">Scale economics: This combination enables synergies related to scale economics of the advertising platform where today there is only one competitor at scale. This includes synergies across both search and non-search related advertising that will strengthen the value proposition to both advertisers and publishers. Additionally, the combination allows us to consolidate capital spending.</p><p page="2" class="ArticleBody">Expanded R&amp;D capacity: The combined talent of our engineering resources can be focused on R&amp;D priorities such as a single search index and single advertising platform. Together we can unleash new levels of innovation, delivering enhanced user experiences, breakthroughs in search, and new advertising platform capabilities. Many of these breakthroughs are a function of an engineering scale that today neither of our companies has on its own.</p><p page="2" class="ArticleBody">Operational efficiencies: Eliminating redundant infrastructure and duplicative operating costs will improve the financial performance of the combined entity.</p><p page="2" class="ArticleBody">Emerging user experiences: Our combined ability to focus engineering resources that drive innovation in emerging scenarios such as video, mobile services, online commerce, social media, and social platforms is greatly enhanced.</p><p page="2" class="ArticleBody">We would value the opportunity to further discuss with you how to optimize the integration of our respective businesses to create a leading global technology company with exceptional display and search advertising capabilities. You should also be aware that we intend to offer significant retention packages to your engineers, key leaders and employees across all disciplines.</p><p page="2" class="ArticleBody">We have dedicated considerable time and resources to an analysis of a potential transaction and are confident that the combination will receive all necessary regulatory approvals. We look forward to discussing this with you, and both our internal legal team and outside counsel are available to meet with your counsel at their earliest convenience.</p><p page="2" class="ArticleBody">Our proposal is subject to the negotiation of a definitive merger agreement and our having the opportunity to conduct certain limited and confirmatory due diligence. In addition, because a portion of the aggregate merger consideration would consist of Microsoft common stock, we would provide Yahoo! the opportunity to conduct appropriate limited due diligence with respect to Microsoft. We are prepared to deliver a draft merger agreement to you and begin discussions immediately.</p><p page="2" class="ArticleBody">In light of the significance of this proposal to your shareholders and ours, as well as the potential for selective disclosures, our intention is to publicly release the text of this letter tomorrow morning.</p><p page="2" class="ArticleBody">Due to the importance of these discussions and the value represented by our proposal, we expect the Yahoo! Board to engage in a full review of our proposal. My leadership team and I would be happy to make ourselves available to meet with you and your Board at your earliest convenience. Depending on the nature of your response, Microsoft reserves the right to pursue all necessary steps to ensure that Yahoo!&#39;s shareholders are provided with the opportunity to realize the value inherent in our proposal.</p><p page="2" class="ArticleBody">We believe this proposal represents a unique opportunity to create significant value for Yahoo!&#39;s shareholders and employees, and the combined company will be better positioned to provide an enhanced value proposition to users and advertisers. We hope that you and your Board share our enthusiasm, and we look forward to a prompt and favorable reply.</p><p page="2" class="ArticleBody">Sincerely yours,</p><p page="2" class="ArticleBody">/s/ Steven A. Ballmer</p><p page="2" class="ArticleBody">Steven A. Ballmer</p><p page="2" class="ArticleBody">Chief Executive Officer</p><p page="2" class="ArticleBody">Microsoft Corporation</p></div>	4	2008-02-01 17:14:35	\N

InfoWorld news	http://www.infoworld.com/cgi-bin/redirect?source=rss&url=http://www.infoworld.com/article/08/02/01/Repairs-to-start-on-undersea-cable-Tuesday_1.html	Repairs to start on undersea cable Tuesday	none	Sci/Tech	<div class="rxbodyfield"><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">Flag Telecom will start repairs next week on a damaged submarine telecommunications cable linking Egypt and Italy. A repair ship is expected to reach the site of the damage, 8.3 kilometers from Alexandria, Egypt, on Tuesday. The repair will take a week to complete, Flag Telecom said Friday.</p><p align="right"><a href="http://ad.doubleclick.net/jump/idg.us.info.rss/news;pos=imu;tile=6;sz=336x280;skey=patch_management;pkey=security;ord=123456789?" target="_blank" /><img src="http://ad.doubleclick.net/ad/idg.us.info.rss/news;pos=imu;tile=6;sz=336x280;skey=patch_management;pkey=security;ord=123456789?" width="336" height="280" border="0" alt="" align="right"/></a></p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">Breaks on Wednesday in the Flag Telecom Europe-Asia cable, owned by India&#39;s Reliance Communications, and on the South East Asia-Middle East-West Europe 4 (SEA-ME-WE 4) cable, owned by a consortium,&#160;<a href="will%20take%20a%20week%20to%20complete">disrupted Internet and other communications to the Middle East and India</a>.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">Flag said the Europe-Asia cable was cut at 8 a.m. GMT on Wednesday. The company also said it was able to restore circuits to some customers and was switching to alternative routes for others.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">A large number of customers in India were shifted by their service providers from the Middle East links to Asia-Pacific routes. But the new routing increased the time-lag heard on long-distance telephone calls, and also led to degradation of Internet service to the U.K. and the East coast of the U.S., said Rajesh Chharia, president of the Internet Service Providers&#39; Association of India (ISPAI).</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">Some analysts said that consumers and smaller customers were suffering even as providers tried to meet their service-level agreements (SLAs) with large corporate customers.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">The Indian government announced late Thursday that Indian service providers, including members of the SEA-ME-WE 4 consortium, are in constant touch with Telecom Egypt to ensure the speedy repair of the SEA-ME-WE 4 and Flag cables connecting India to Western Europe. Repairing this type of submarine optical fiber cable typically takes 15 days, but the Indian ministry of communications and information technology expects this link will be completely restored within 10 days.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">Another submarine Internet cable owned by Flag Telecom, the Falcon cable between the United Arab Emirates and Oman, was cut on Friday at 6 a.m. GMT, at a location 56 kilometers from Dubai, Flag said Friday. A repair ship has been notified, and is expected to arrive at the site of the damage in the next few days, the company said.</p></div>	4	2008-02-01 18:36:13	\N

InfoWorld news	http://www.infoworld.com/cgi-bin/redirect?source=rss&url=http://www.infoworld.com/article/08/02/01/Privacy-groups-vow-to-fight-Microsoft-Yahoo-deal_1.html	Privacy groups vow to fight Microsoft-Yahoo deal	none	Sci/Tech	<div class="rxbodyfield"><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">Privacy groups are promising a fight before U.S. regulatory agencies if&#160;<a href="http://www.infoworld.com/article/08/02/01/Microsoft-offers-to-buy-Yahoo-for-44-billion_1.html">Microsoft&#39;s offer to buy Yahoo</a>&#160;for $44.6 billion is accepted, and the deal could face significant hurdles in Europe as well.</p><p align="right"><a href="http://ad.doubleclick.net/jump/idg.us.info.rss/news;pos=imu;tile=6;sz=336x280;skey=patch_management;pkey=security;ord=123456789?" target="_blank" /><img src="http://ad.doubleclick.net/ad/idg.us.info.rss/news;pos=imu;tile=6;sz=336x280;skey=patch_management;pkey=security;ord=123456789?" width="336" height="280" border="0" alt="" align="right"/></a></p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">Microsoft announced that it&#160;<a href="http://www.infoworld.com/article/08/02/01/Microsoft-offer-to-Yahoo-board_1.html">sent an offer to Yahoo&#39;s board of directors</a>&#160;on Thursday, going public with the news Friday morning. Immediately, the executive directors of the Center for Digital Democracy (CDD) and the Electronic Privacy Information Center (EPIC) said the acquisition would raise serious privacy concerns.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">CDD will press the U.S. Department of Justice, the Federal Trade Commission and Congress to &quot;scrutinize this deal and impose the needed safeguards for it -- and the industry,&quot; said Jeffrey Chester, CDD&#39;s executive director. CDD and EPIC tried to stop Google&#39;s proposed acquisition of online ad service DoubleClick on privacy grounds before the FTC last year, but the FTC approved the deal in December.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">The Microsoft-Yahoo deal, if consummated, would &quot;create a powerful interactive Internet duopoly in online media,&quot; Chester said. &quot;Google and Microsoft will have inordinate power to shape the online communications marketplace, including journalism, entertainment and advertising. There are consequences to democratic societies everywhere, as two digital gatekeepers are likely to control how the Internet and other interactive media evolve.&quot;</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">The proposed deal also underscores a need for new laws or regulations that protect consumer data, Chester added. &quot;In an era when individuals are increasingly conducting their personal, social and political lives online, the corporations that control the digital experience will have a far-reaching influence over every aspect of society,&quot; he said. &quot;Consumers will be more vulnerable to having their personal information become the property of the GoogleClick&#39;s and Microhoo&#39;s.&quot;</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">But the DOJ and FTC may have little grounds to oppose a Microsoft/Yahoo merger, said Professor Keith Hylton, who specializes in antitrust issues at the Boston University law school. While Microsoft and Yahoo compete in some areas, Microsoft could argue this a &quot;vertical&quot; merger that largely expands its online services, but largely doesn&#39;t eliminate competition, he said.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">&quot;I think Microsoft is trying to ramp up in the online services/online ad revenue business,&quot; Hylton said. &quot;Microsoft is a small player in that area, and Google is a big player. This is a merger of two firms trying to compete against a big monster out there -- Google.&quot;</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">But the deal could face more hurdles in Europe. If the deal allows Microsoft to take components of Windows online, and &quot;in the process increases Microsoft&#39;s dominance of the market for PC operating systems,&quot; then the European Commission would have to prohibit the deal, said an antitrust lawyer in Europe who asked not to be identified.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">European Union merger rules prohibit dominant companies from increasing their dominance, the lawyer said.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">The combined company would likely have sell off an instant-messaging service, added a European Commission official familiar with the competition department. &quot;I can&#39;t see how Microsoft/Yahoo would be allowed to keep both instant-messaging services,&quot; said the official, who also asked not to be identified.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">Microsoft campaigned for federal regulators to block the Google-DoubleClick deal, partly on antitrust grounds. But Google argued the acquisition would join two companies operating in different online markets.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">This week, Judge Colleen Kollar-Kotelly of the U.S. District Court for the District of Columbia extended antitrust scrutiny of Microsoft for two years. But the U.S. government&#39;s antitrust case against Microsoft was based on its desktop and server operating systems, not online services. If anything, the old antitrust case could help Microsoft make the case for approval of its acquisition of Yahoo, Hylton said.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">&quot;I assume Microsoft people can say, &#39;Look, we&#39;re already under a microscope, doesn&#39;t this suggest we&#39;re less likely to do anticompetitive things?&#39;&quot; Hylton said.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">But a consolidating online market means users will have their data held by a small number of companies, said Professor Joseph Turow, at University of Pennsylvania school of communication.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">&quot;Microsoft&#39;s decision to buy Yahoo is a direct result of the decision by the FTC to allow Google to purchase DoubleClick,&quot; he said. &quot;It is further evidence that despite the appearance of unlimited choice in the new media environment, people&#39;s activities will be tracked and shaped by a very small number of companies who care far more about surveillance and targeted advertising than the public interest.&quot;</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">The public needs to demand privacy scrutiny in the proposed deal, he said. &quot;The federal government, which should have been the guardian of the public interest, has dropped the ball.&quot;</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody"><em>(Additional reporting by Paul Meller in Brussels.)</em></p></div>	4	2008-02-01 19:44:59	\N

Scripting News	http://www.scripting.com/stories/2008/02/01/yahooMicrosoft.html	Yahoo + Microsoft	none	Software and Developement	Should Yahoo accept Microsoft's offer? <br><br>\
Sure. What else do they have to do?<br><br>\
Most tech companies are pretty aimless, people think there's a grand plan to Apple or Google, but I bet there isn't. They just throw stuff up on the wall, if it sticks, do version 2.0. <img src="http://www.scripting.com/gifs/QBullets/qbullets/sidesmiley.gif" width="11" height="11" border="0" alt="smile"><br><br>\
Does Yahoo + Microsoft make sense?<br><br>\
Nahh. It's like the dead leading the blind.<br><br>\
The only reason the deal makes sense is because it's the only thing either company could do that anyone might possibly <a href="http://www.techmeme.com/080201/p26#a080201p26">care</a> about.<br><br>\
It would make more sense for Twitter to acquire Yahoo. At least then they'd get some servers that could stay up for 24 hours straight. <img src="http://www.scripting.com/gifs/QBullets/qbullets/sidesmiley.gif" width="11" height="11" border="0" alt="smile"><br><br>\
Anyway, I might have been too hard on em. But then again...<br><br>\

<blockquote>\
This week I started to setup a Debian-based (Etch) web-server with PHP 5.2 in a virtual-machine with VMWare. Part of this setup was getting XDebug2 integrated. It's really awesome and my students definitely need to learn about it. [...] Building went well as usual but when I tried to integrate the extension inside php.ini it was all weird.\
</blockquote>\
<p>\
His system kept throwing him an error when he tried to load the shared module using the zend_extension directive, hand things happened. Loading it normally worked (so he knew it wasn't the module) and he finally figured out the problem:\
</p>\
<blockquote>\
But I need to enable it as Zend extension. Whatever. I finally used the full path to xdebug.so to load it [...] that worked. \

Matches start at six pm, but you can show up a little early if you'd like to trade cards. As always new players are welcome, just bring a starter deck. It's also a good idea to register at Go-Pokemon.com and bring your POP ID. A reader wrote in today to tell me that he was doing the New York Times crossword puzzle for January 30th and noticed this clue for 12 down:  "Tycho's pal in the webcomic 'Penny Arcade' (4 letters)." That's totally awesome. I'm sure the Force Unleashed will be fine. The time period around the original trilogy is just getting so crowded. Now Vader has a secret apprentice? I mean, it makes sense canonically to me. The Emperor had Mara Jade out there doing his dirty work. It's not unreasonable to think Vader had a similar arrangement. Also the very nature of Sith rule makes covering your ass a necessity. The hook for the game is fine and I don't mind the 3rd person action stuff. There are a few games I'd much rather see them make though. The fact that they have not made a sequel to Republic Commando is fucking criminal. That's not a joke either. I mean that someone over there should be put in jail for the rest of their life. RepCom was an incredible squad based shooter, and unlike most games in that genre it was packed with awesome characters. This games deserves a next gen sequel. The other game that needs a next gen installment is Tie Fighter. Seriously that game came out in 1994 and it's one of the best space shooters ever. And for fucks sake stop setting things during the movies. There's nearly sixty years worth of incredible content (minus the dark nest series) extending out past Return of the Jedi. You don't have to keep trying to cram stories into the same 20 year period. They're milking so much content out of that period that eventually we'll be playing a game as Luke where the goal is to repair vaporators on the south ridge. Hurry up you've only got 'till mid day!Rez is available on Xbox Live now. It's one of the best games ever made.   The most popular piece of clothing we've ever made, AKA The Black Mantle is back in stock. It's joined by its polar opposite, the Luminous Vestments. PHPDeveloper.org	http://www.phpdeveloper.org/news/9548	Stubbles Blog: Stubbles 0.5.0 released	http___www.phpdeveloper.org_img_ads_dcphpcon2008.jpg.gif	Software and Developement	<p>\
<i>Frank Kleine</i> has <a href="http://www.stubbles.org/archives/41-Stubbles-0.5.0-released.html">announced on the Stubbles blog</a> that the latest version of the framework, Stubbles 0.5.0 has been released.\
</p>\
<blockquote>\
A last day of a month - time to release a new Stubbles version. The release does not feature that much new features, we focused mainly on infrastructure and code quality improvements. The most important change of course is the change of the package separator.\
</blockquote>\
<p>\
Instead of the dots they've gone with the more standard double-colon that PHP already uses. There were also code quality improvements and a move away from SimpleTest out to the popular <a href="http://www.phpunit.de">PHPUnit</a> unit testing package.\
</p>\
<p>\
You can download this new package from the <a href="http://www.stubbles.net/">Stubbles project site</a>.\

\	</ul>\

\	</p>\

\	<li>Develop, maintain and support large, high-availability, web based internal applications and reporting tools; support high-traffic commercial websites\
\	<li>Interest in creating the next generation of interactive media applications\
\	<li>Research new platforms and architecture to support current and future business requirements\
\	<li>Ensure consistency and adherence to MODE's standards, processes, and policies for all projects.\
\	</ul>\

\	</ul>\
\	<li>2+ years web development experience\
\	<li>experience in client facing communications\
\	<li>Computer Science degree or equivalent experience\
\	<li>Excellent analytical/problem solving skills, ability to think creatively and solve complex technical problems\
\	<li>Quality oral/written communication and interpersonal skills in order to effectively partner with the technologies and business communities\
\	<li>Ability to develop a clear understanding of client needs and plan applications to meet their needs.\
\	</ul>\
\	<p>As a MODE team member, you'll be rewarded with:</p>\
\	</ul>\
\	<li>A fun, friendly work environment\
\	<li>Competitive salary commensurate with experience\
\	<li>Casual dress code\
\	<li>Performance-based bonus\
\	<li>Generous paid vacation (19 floating days, 6 holidays)\
\	<li>100% employee covered medical benefits\
\	<li>Possible relocation assistance\
\	<li>Great North Carolina weather\
\	</ul>\
\	<p>If interested we ask that you write a cover letter including the following:</p>\
\	</ul>\
\	<li>Why you are right for our position\
\	<li>Your salary requirements\
\	<li>A set of 3 urls that demonstrate work you are most proud of including a brief description of your role on each project\
\	</ul>\

International Herald Tribune	http://www.newsisfree.com/iclick/i,259502644,1210,f/	GM January U.S. sales up 2.6 percent, Ford and Toyota decline	none	Business	\N	5	2008-02-01 22:23:05	\N
International Herald Tribune	http://www.newsisfree.com/iclick/i,259499387,1210,f/	Microsoft bids $44.6 billion for Yahoo	none	Business	\N	5	2008-02-01 23:56:29	\N
InfoWorld news	http://www.infoworld.com/cgi-bin/redirect?source=rss&url=http://www.infoworld.com/article/08/02/01/Yahoo-bid-could-backfire-lest-Microsoft-changes-ways_1.html	Yahoo bid could backfire lest Microsoft changes ways	none	Sci/Tech	<div class="rxbodyfield"><p page="1" class="ArticleBody"><a href="http://www.infoworld.com/article/08/02/01/Microsoft-offers-to-buy-Yahoo-for-44-billion_1.html">Microsoft&#39;s $44.6 billion offer to purchase Yahoo</a>&#160;is a dramatic statement from a company that delayed acknowledging the importance of emerging Web business models for so long, it faced becoming an also-ran in the Web 2.0 economy.</p><p align="right"><a href="http://ad.doubleclick.net/jump/idg.us.info.rss/news;pos=imu;tile=6;sz=336x280;skey=patch_management;pkey=security;ord=123456789?" target="_blank" /><img src="http://ad.doubleclick.net/ad/idg.us.info.rss/news;pos=imu;tile=6;sz=336x280;skey=patch_management;pkey=security;ord=123456789?" width="336" height="280" border="0" alt="" align="right"/></a></p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">But the cultural implications of the move are so tricky that the deal could end up backfiring for both vendors if Microsoft doesn&#39;t take care to learn from its past and use Yahoo to transform its business and&#160;not just help bolster its unproven efforts in online advertising and hosted services.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">The unprecedented deal, which would put a sizable dent in Microsoft&#39;s wallet, would be the largest purchase ever for the company. If Microsoft is willing to spend that much money, it also has to be willing to change some old ways of thinking to make the most out of the investment, analysts say.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">To achieve this, analysts caution Microsoft to be careful not to view Yahoo as a one-trick pony, taken onboard only for its user base and infrastructure to bolster Microsoft&#39;s online advertising interests against Google. While this is certainly the primary reason for the deal, to make the most of it, Microsoft has to not only respect the strength of Yahoo&#39;s brand but also be willing to let go of some of its own traditional proprietary interests -- not just on the product side but in its culture as well.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">Microsoft has never been one to let go of its vision or proprietary interests too easily; when acquiring companies, it usually subsumes the products and services and brands them as its own.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">While this has worked in the past because Microsoft traditionally has shied away from acquiring big-name or big-ticket items --&#160;<a href="http://www.infoworld.com/article/07/05/18/microsoft-to-buy-aquantive_1.html">last year&#39;s $6 billion aQuantive deal</a>&#160;was a notable exception -- it&#39;s not as simple to do this with a company like Yahoo, analysts said.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">In the areas of online search and particular services and as an online destination for users, Yahoo is a stronger brand than Microsoft. Microsoft must recognize this and be willing to give up some of its interest in new content and services branded, respectively, under MSN and Windows Live to make the deal successful, said Ned May, director and lead analyst for market research firm Outsell.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">&quot;The big question is, will Microsoft take this and recognize it for being a stronger property and migrate its efforts there, or will it try to push its own efforts out through Yahoo?&quot; he asked. &quot;Historically, there&#39;s no precedent for it to do anything but use [an acquired company] to get Microsoft&#39;s message out.&quot;</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">Though Microsoft and Yahoo are different types of companies and the union itself makes much more sense, Ron Schmelzer, analyst and managing partner with Zapthink, likened the deal to Time Warner-AOL, in which AOL&#39;s brand was damaged, not enhanced, after all was said and done.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">But investing as much as the gross domestic product of some countries in one company could inspire Microsoft to &quot;change its stripes&quot; and rethink its own interests, he said.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">To make the deal a true success, Microsoft also has to prove that it can let go of its entrenched Windows OS and desktop software culture, which had been the anchor keeping Microsoft from moving more quickly against Google and Yahoo in online advertising and services in the first place, Schmelzer said.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">&quot;The application itself is moving away from the thing that sits captive on your desktop to the thing that&#39;s distributed on the Internet,&quot; he said. &quot;Microsoft has to rid itself of its &#39;80s and &#39;90s perspective -- which was great in the &#39;80s and &#39;90s, but now 80 percent of the value of the computer is not in the computer itself.&quot;</p><p page="2" class="ArticleBody">Microsoft had been moving in this direction before Friday&#39;s news, but it has been burdened by its need to keep the customers of two of its biggest consumer products -- Windows and Office -- happy, as well as its enormous portfolio of enterprise and business customers. Instead of moving full bore into the Web, Microsoft had adopted a &quot;software plus services&quot; strategy as a nod to its software legacy and inability to move fully to a more services-oriented strategy because of it.</p><p page="2" class="ArticleBody">Still, some think an entire cultural shift isn&#39;t necessary for Microsoft to make the most out of the deal. David Mitchell Smith, vice president and fellow at Gartner, said Microsoft can leverage Yahoo successfully without changing its usual way of doing things, by keeping the brand and merging the best parts of Yahoo&#39;s Internet business, such as its online content, advertising and search, with its online services efforts.</p><p page="2" class="ArticleBody">&quot;I would expect to see the Yahoo brand come out of this very, very strong,&quot; he said. In particular, Microsoft has been making moves to drive more video and other multimedia content online through MSN, and that is one area where the company could give up its own identity in favor of Yahoo&#39;s, Smith said.</p><p page="2" class="ArticleBody">Andrew Brust, chief, new technology for consulting firm twentysix New York, said that the combination of Microsoft&#39;s existing Web technology and the Yahoo brand would be &quot;nicely complementary,&quot; though he acknowledged the risks of such a union. Even so, &quot;risk aversion is not a good Internet strategy,&quot; Brust said. Taking a risk in this area as well as bringing &quot;some truly Internet-focused mindset into the corporate culture&quot; may be just what Microsoft needs.</p><p page="2" class="ArticleBody">Others likened the deal to another risky one, HP-Compaq, which many feared would be a disaster because of product overlap and cultural differences. That deal eventually proved successful.</p><p page="2" class="ArticleBody">However, it&#39;s important to keep in mind how much more of a role that culture and the cool factor plays on the Internet than it does in the world of traditional computer hardware, warned Outsell&#39;s May. He said Yahoo users may be put off by the notion of Microsoft as their new daddy and see Google as the lesser of two evils, which would defeat the notion of the Microsoft-Yahoo union in the first place.</p></div>	4	2008-02-01 23:45:12	\N

PHPDeveloper.org	http://www.phpdeveloper.org/news/9549	Rob Thompson's Blog: Switch vs. If	http___www.phpdeveloper.org_img_ads_dcphpcon2008.jpg.gif	Software and Developement	<p>\
<i>Rob Thompson</i> has <a href="http://rob.sun3.org/php-code/switch-vs-if/">posted about</a> some simple benchmarking he did comparing the speed of a series of "if" statements versus one "switch" with multiple cases.\
</p>\
<blockquote>\
I got curious about which is actually more efficient at matching a random integer with a set of conditionals. So, I setup a script to create a set of large scripts to test the speed of these different constructs. Using the 'time' command, I measured the speed at which the condition could match a random number.\
</blockquote>\
<p>\
His results found that the switch statement is generally more than 2 times as fast at matching a simple integer. His tests, however, didn't go through much more than this simple test. It'd be interesting to see what it would do with something more complex (like longer strings or handling the result of an evaluation inside the definition of the switch().\
</p>	3	2008-02-02 00:15:35	\N

SourceForge.net Project News	http://www.pheedo.com/click.phdo?i=e270264ca013ffe2fee1a031338de2f0	SMPlayer: Version 0.6.0rc1 released	none	Software and Developement	SMPlayer is a complete front-end for MPlayer, from basic features like playing videos, DVDs, VCDs to more advanced features like support for MPlayer filters, edl lists, and more.\
\
\
Most important changes since 0.5.62:\
\
 * Added support for pls playlist files.\
 * Better accuracy on subtitle selection. Fixes problems with mp4 embedded \
   subtitles. Requires mplayer svn r25158 or above.\
 * Now the screensaver and powersave on Windows is really turned off, even on\
   Windows Vista.\
 * The cache setting is independent for each type of media.\
 * Added an option which allows to fix the problem of loud volume on startup\
   (requires a patched mplayer).\
 * (Windows) The file associations code has been improved. Now it should work\
   better in Windows Vista as well as other versions of Windows.\
 * New option Video->Add black borders, which replaces the letterbox options \
   in Video->Aspect ratio.\
 * (Windows) Work-around for a mplayer bug: now filenames with characters \
   outside the local codepage can be opened, by passing to mplayer the short \
   version of the filename. This can be enabled in Preferences->Advanced.\
 * Now the H.264 loop filter can be disabled for High Definition videos only\
   (720p and above).\
 * Possibility to update the video while dragging the time slider.\
 * New icons for the default theme.\
 * SSA/ASS subtitles can also be resized during playback. Requires at least \
   mplayer r25843.\
 * Now it's possible to zoom out the video image.\
 * New Help->About dialog.\
 * New option Help->FAQ which will show the FAQ.\
 * Bugfix: the colorkey is passed properly to mplayer.\
 * Added the Finnish and the Korean translations.<br style="clear: both;"/>\

InfoWorld news	http://www.infoworld.com/cgi-bin/redirect?source=rss&url=http://www.infoworld.com/article/08/02/01/Microsoft-could-stumble-in-quest-for-ad-speed_1.html	Microsoft could stumble in quest for ad speed	none	Sci/Tech	<div class="rxbodyfield"><p class="ArticleBody" page="1">Microsoft executives said very little on Friday about the undeniable challenges of integrating the company&#39;s Internet division with Yahoo, largely avoiding the proverbial elephant in the room that could delay or, in some cases, eliminate benefits of the deal.</p><p align="right"><a href="http://ad.doubleclick.net/jump/idg.us.info.rss/news;pos=imu;tile=6;sz=336x280;skey=patch_management;pkey=security;ord=123456789?" target="_blank" /><img src="http://ad.doubleclick.net/ad/idg.us.info.rss/news;pos=imu;tile=6;sz=336x280;skey=patch_management;pkey=security;ord=123456789?" width="336" height="280" border="0" alt="" align="right"/></a></p><p class="ArticleBody" page="1">At the heart of the acquisition is Microsoft&#39;s goal of giving its online advertising and online services business a major boost, ending years of business and technology defeats at the hands of common rival Google.</p><p class="ArticleBody" page="1">Microsoft wants to make sure that as online ad spending doubles to about $80 billion in the next three years, it will be in a much better position to grab a larger piece of the market, specifically in sponsored search, which is the biggest online ad segment and where Google dominates.</p><p class="ArticleBody" page="1">As CEO Steve Ballmer, President of Platforms &amp; Services Division Kevin Johnson and Chief Software Architect Ray Ozzie said repeatedly during Friday&#39;s news conference, Microsoft wants to swallow Yahoo to accelerate its pace in online advertising. With Yahoo&#39;s online services, engineers, and ad platforms, Microsoft hopes to become a stronger competitor to Google than it is today.</p><p class="ArticleBody" page="1">That all sounds fine in theory, but Ballmer and his colleagues said little about the energy and know-how they will need to make this proposed $44.6 billion acquisition work, considering that the companies have a significant overlap in online services, markedly different cultures, and an abundance of inflated professional egos at every level.</p><p class="ArticleBody" page="1">Not to mention that Yahoo these days is far from functioning as a well-oiled machine. Yahoo has been in significant turmoil for more than a year. Seasoned executives who are experts on its business have struggled and largely failed to restore the company&#39;s technical edge and business focus. That&#39;s a mess that Microsoft will inherit and will have to solve in order for the deal to work its expected magic.</p><p class="ArticleBody" page="1">In short, Microsoft must make sure that, in its quest for scale and speed, it doesn&#39;t end up getting stuck, its wheels spinning, trying to mesh Yahoo with MSN, while Google speeds further ahead. It&#39;s clear that to take advantage of the online ad growth, companies will need to innovate and change quickly, and not be sidetracked by acquisition distractions.</p><p class="ArticleBody" page="1">Among the many emerging opportunities in online advertising are: the mobile sector, which is expected to go from almost nonexistent to vibrant in the coming years; social Web properties, such as social networks, blogs and social news sites, which haven&#39;t been monetized properly and hold great promise; and video, both in the form of video ads and ads in videos.</p><p class="ArticleBody" page="1">There were indications during Friday&#39;s news conference that Microsoft may not have taken the time to fully assess the magnitude of the integration complications. Despite Ballmer&#39;s assurances that he personally has thought &quot;long and hard&quot; about the Yahoo acquisition, there is evidently a level of urgency about the move, or else the deal wouldn&#39;t have been an unsolicited offer, as Yahoo has portrayed it.</p><p class="ArticleBody" page="1">If, as Ballmer indicated, the companies have been in on-and-off talks for about 18 months about a possible acquisition, it&#39;s fair to ask -- as a financial analyst did -- why they couldn&#39;t sit down privately and present, jointly, a more cooked deal. Basically, Ballmer admitted that Google keeps expanding its empire and time is of the essence.</p><p class="ArticleBody" page="1">&quot;Any large integration process has risks associated with it. We&#39;ve all thought about it. We could have hired [more] engineers, but at the same time the market continues to grow and the leader continues to consolidate positions and there&#39;s nothing quite like putting together two larger sophisticated R&amp;D organizations,&quot; Ballmer said.</p><p class="ArticleBody" page="2">Along with the inherent opportunity to sell more ads, Nick Patience, managing analyst at The 451 Group, also sees a &quot;potential integration headache&quot; with having to integrate Microsoft&#39;s ad platforms -- AdCenter and aQuantive -- with Yahoo&#39;s. Patience is also skeptical about the possibility of merging search indexes, and believes that the search engines will most likely have to continue to operate independently. Overall, the integration work would represent for Microsoft &quot;a step into the unknown,&quot; particularly since this would be by far the largest acquisition in Microsoft&#39;s history, Patience said.</p><p class="ArticleBody" page="2">Gartner analyst Allen Weiner also sees potential integration challenges, particularly because he doesn&#39;t think either organization has a powerful leader who can take the reins of the combined entity and lead it into the future. &quot;They need someone like a Steve Jobs or a Bill Gates who has the charisma, vision, technical knowledge, and consumer knowledge to lead,&quot; Weiner said.</p><p class="ArticleBody" page="2">On paper the acquisition has interesting potential, but it will all come down to how the integration is carried out, Weiner said. &quot;It&#39;s all about the execution,&quot; he said. &quot;The devil is in the details.&quot;</p><p class="ArticleBody" page="2">Despite numerous acquisitions over the past few years in advertising and Web 2.0 technologies, Yahoo has struggled to jump-start its business, said JupiterResearch analyst Michael Gartenberg. &quot;At the end of the day, it hasn&#39;t all worked out for them,&quot; he said.</p><p class="ArticleBody" page="2">While Microsoft executives are stressing that a deal with Yahoo would give it the scale to compete with Google, wrapping the two companies&#39; diverse technologies together won&#39;t be simple, Gartenberg said. &quot;In order to get to that scale, you&#39;ve got to be able to fit all those pieces and parts together,&quot; he said.</p><p class="ArticleBody" page="2">Despite the integration concerns, Microsoft has good processes in place for managing acquisitions of large companies, said Gartner analyst Mike McGuire. However, it will be key for Microsoft to quickly put a senior management team in place as Google will continue to propel ahead as Microsoft sorts out the details. &quot;They are going to have to start showing some traction, or at least a really solid vision for how they will combine the companies ... early on,&quot; McGuire said.</p><p class="ArticleBody" page="2">Matt Booth, a Kelsey Group analyst, thinks that the integration challenges will be major but predicts that Microsoft will work through them methodically, starting on the back end and linking services in a way that, as much as possible, is transparent to end-users, be they advertisers, publishers, or consumers. For services that are just too difficult to integrate, they will likely be kept separate. The last thing Microsoft wants to do is drive users away, Booth said.</p><p class="ArticleBody" page="2">In a research note, Citigroup financial analyst Mark Mahaney said he is skeptical that a combined Microsoft-Yahoo would improve its search products enough to affect Google&#39;s position, since they both have been losing search market share and, in his opinion, seeing a decrease in their search innovation.</p><p class="ArticleBody" page="2">&quot;Given what would surely be immense integration challenges, it&#8217;s hard for us to see how a Microsoft-Yahoo combination would create a greater technology competitor to Google at least for the foreseeable future,&quot; he wrote.</p><p class="ArticleBody" page="2">&quot;We could see a scenario by which Google would actually gain more market share due to industry uncertainty over the integration of the deal,&quot; Mahaney added.</p></div>	4	2008-02-02 01:10:30	\N

PHPDeveloper.org	http://www.phpdeveloper.org/news/9552	PHPClasses.org: A PHP killer feature - Streams abstraction	http___www.phpdeveloper.org_img_ads_dcphpcon2008.jpg.gif	Software and Developement	<p>\
On the PHPClasses.org website there's a <a href="http://www.phpclasses.org/blog/post/74-A-PHP-killer-feature--Streams-abstraction.html">new entry</a> covering, among other things, one handy feature PHP includes to let developers read and write their data more flexibly - <a href="http://us.php.net/stream">streams</a>.\
</p>\
<blockquote>\
This article explains what are stream handlers and how they simplify PHP developers lives by allowing PHP applications to easily read and write data from containers, like remote Web pages or e-mail messages, as if they were files. [...] The article also presents more examples of cool stream handlers classes submitted to the PHPClasses site by several authors.\
</blockquote>\
<p>\
He <a href="http://www.phpclasses.org/blog/post/74-A-PHP-killer-feature--Streams-abstraction.html">describes</a> the abstraction that the streams interface allows, how they can make your life easier, a real-life example of streams in action (working with POP3) and some of the classes that have been contributed to PHPClasses.org that use them.\
