InfoWorld news	http://www.infoworld.com/cgi-bin/redirect?source=rss&url=http://www.infoworld.com/article/08/02/01/PHP-5-deadline-approaches_1.html	PHP 5 deadline approaches	none	Sci/Tech	<div class="rxbodyfield"><p class="ArticleBody" page="1">A Tuesday deadline has been set in which several leading open-source PHP (Hypertext Preprocessor) projects plan to stop supporting older versions of PHP in upcoming releases.</p><p align="right"><a href="http://ad.doubleclick.net/jump/idg.us.info.rss/news;pos=imu;tile=6;sz=336x280;skey=patch_management;pkey=security;ord=123456789?" target="_blank" /><img src="http://ad.doubleclick.net/ad/idg.us.info.rss/news;pos=imu;tile=6;sz=336x280;skey=patch_management;pkey=security;ord=123456789?" width="336" height="280" border="0" alt="" align="right"/></a></p><p class="ArticleBody" page="1">The <a href="http://gophp5.org/" class="regularArticleU">Go PHP 5</a> campaign, sponsored by several PHP proponents, is intended to move the PHP developer community fully onto the PHP version 5 platform. Among the projects backing the effort are <a href="http://www.symfony-project.org/" class="regularArticleU">Symfony</a>, <a href="http://typo3.com/" class="regularArticleU">Typo3</a>, phpMyAdmin, <a href="http://drupal.org/" class="regularArticleU">Drupal,</a> Propel, and Doctrine. These vendors are committing to use PHP 5.2 in releases developed after Tuesday.</p><p class="ArticleBody" page="1">Campaign advocates also have issued an invitation to other PHP projects to participate, and so far, about 150 software projects and about 200 Web hosters have committed.</p><p class="ArticleBody" page="1">Most PHP Web applications run in PHP 4 and 5. PHP 4 was released in 2000, while PHP 5 became available in 2004.</p><p class="ArticleBody" page="1">"We think PHP is absolutely the platform going forward," said Mark de Visser, chief marketing officer at PHP tools vendor Zend Technologies, which is supporting the Go PHP5 effort.</p><p class="ArticleBody" page="1">PHP 5 features object orientation, for enterprise application development, and Web services capabilities, de Visser said. But adoption has been slow because of issues like Web hosts that offer PHP 4 by default, Go PHP 5 said.</p><p class="ArticleBody" page="1">"No one's moving to PHP 5 because no one wants to be first," said Larry Garfield, a co-founder of the Go PHP 5 project.</p><p class="ArticleBody" page="1">Hosts will not upgrade until projects do, but projects will not upgrade until hosts do, thus presenting a chicken-and-egg situation, according to Go PHP 5's July 2007 statement. Go PHP 5 hopes to give Web hosts incentive to upgrade servers to newer versions of PHP.</p><p class="ArticleBody" page="1">Additionally, extensions to the PHP 4 platform are ceasing, according to Garfield. There will only be major security issues considered between now and August, and after that, PHP development stops, he said.</p><p class="ArticleBody" page="1">PHP 6, meanwhile, is not due for more than a year, de Visser said. It will focus on internationalization, he said.</p></div>	4	2008-02-02 02:23:48	\N

InfoWorld news	http://www.infoworld.com/cgi-bin/redirect?source=rss&url=http://www.infoworld.com/article/08/02/01/SF-area-subway-gets-fast-Wi-Fi-in-test_1.html	SF-area subway gets fast Wi-Fi in test	none	Sci/Tech	<div class="rxbodyfield"><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">A startup says it can give subway riders wireless Internet access that&#39;s faster than most home broadband in the U.S.</p><p align="right"><a href="http://ad.doubleclick.net/jump/idg.us.info.rss/news;pos=imu;tile=6;sz=336x280;skey=patch_management;pkey=security;ord=123456789?" target="_blank" /><img src="http://ad.doubleclick.net/ad/idg.us.info.rss/news;pos=imu;tile=6;sz=336x280;skey=patch_management;pkey=security;ord=123456789?" width="336" height="280" border="0" alt="" align="right"/></a></p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">Tests at stations and on a special stretch of track in the Bay Area Rapid Transit (BART) system around San Francisco showed that Wi-Fi Rail&#39;s patent-pending technology delivered more than 15Mbps of wireless throughput to riders and people waiting for trains, the company said. Wi-Fi Rail hopes to roll out such networks on rail systems around the world and charge commuters for access.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">Commuter rail, with thousands of daily riders, could represent a rich opportunity for public wireless Internet access. Wi-Fi hotspots in airports and coffee shops have drawn some paying users, but the hotspots are useful more for occasional than for regular use. And citywide public Wi-Fi networks, often planned out with local governments, have run into political and business problems.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">Wi-Fi Rail, founded in 2006 and based near Sacramento, would build two kinds of Wi-Fi networks: one in the cars and one around the tracks, said Michael Cromar, Wi-Fi Rail&#39;s CFO. Passengers would log in to access points on each car, and each car&#39;s network would lock on to one access point after another along the rail system. The trackside access points, in turn, would feed traffic onto fiber-optic lines. Roaming would be handled by the in-car network and be transparent to users, Cromar said.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">Even better than typical home broadband, the network can deliver its average 15Mbps speed both upstream and downstream, according to Wi-Fi Rail. Passengers would share that link, but in tests, there was no noticeable slowdown between one passenger and eight passengers using the network, Cromar said. The system worked with the trains moving at speeds as high as 65 miles per hour.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">The company tested its technology in both underground and above-ground parts of the BART system. Above ground, Wi-Fi Rail used standard outdoor access points with line-of-sight antennas to form a link from trains as they went by. In an underground test, the company used &quot;leaky&quot; coaxial cable, a technology some rail systems already use for exchanging operational data with cars, according to Cromar. The leaky cable is deliberately unshielded so signals traveling along it can be picked up all through a tunnel.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">In-car tests took place on a 2.6-mile BART test track last month, as well as on a stretch of tunnel in San Francisco. Another part of the test proved such a service can draw customers, Cromar said. Wi-Fi Rail set up regular access points in four underground stations in downtown San Francisco and let people waiting for trains register and use the network for free. Without any publicity, more than 6,400 people signed up in less than six months, he said.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">Although BART hosted the tests, it hasn&#39;t made a deal to have such a network deployed, Cromar said. But Wi-Fi Rail has talked with one interested transit system in the U.S. and is working with a partner to approach a rail system in another country, he said. The company said its technology is ready to go and could be used for anything that follows a predetermined path, including highways.</p></div>	4	2008-02-02 03:27:27	\N
InfoWorld news	http://www.infoworld.com/cgi-bin/redirect?source=rss&url=http://www.infoworld.com/article/08/02/01/Yahoo-a-mere-front-end-for-Microsoft-hosted-apps_1.html	Yahoo a mere front end for Microsoft hosted apps?	none	Sci/Tech	<div class="rxbodyfield"><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">While dealing logistically and technically with their overlapping online offerings will certainly prove troublesome&#160;<a href="http://www.infoworld.com/archives/t.jsp?N=s&amp;V=95033">if its bid to purchase Yahoo</a>&#160;succeeds, Microsoft will at least have an immediate outlet for bringing more of its traditional desktop portfolio to the Web and to a broader customer base.</p><p align="right"><a href="http://ad.doubleclick.net/jump/idg.us.info.rss/news;pos=imu;tile=6;sz=336x280;skey=patch_management;pkey=security;ord=123456789?" target="_blank" /><img src="http://ad.doubleclick.net/ad/idg.us.info.rss/news;pos=imu;tile=6;sz=336x280;skey=patch_management;pkey=security;ord=123456789?" width="336" height="280" border="0" alt="" align="right"/></a></p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">Microsoft has been trying for more than two years to find a critical mass to adopt new online services beyond search, e-mail, and instant messaging under the Windows Live brand -- with little success. Its early MSN e-mail and IM offerings are popular enough with Web users; however, users of Google and Yahoo online services have been loath to adopt the revamped Windows Live offerings in favor of the ones they&#39;re already using.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">Not only could that change if the company purchases Yahoo, but Microsoft also will have a ready-made Web front end for rolling out more of its desktop applications as services, said Paul Fox, CIO of Guy Carpenter, a New York-based reinsurance company.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">&quot;The Yahoo platform is really what they&#39;re buying,&quot; he said. &quot;With Yahoo, they&#39;re tapping into the base culture of the Internet online community that&#39;s matured over the last 10 years. It&#39;s going to make it easier for people to take a look at and try their services, whereas before it had to be a more conscious effort.&quot;</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">Aside from the usual raft of consumer applications&#160;such as&#160;search, e-mail, maps, and the like, Microsoft already has brought some of its many business desktop applications -- such as Office and CRM -- online in hosted, though often scaled-down, versions.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">Access to Yahoo&#39;s estimated 500 million visitors per month will give it a new channel to deliver what the company now calls its &quot;software plus services&quot; strategy, as well as buy the company time to bring more competitive versions of applications that were originally coded for the desktop to the Web.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">Indeed, in the conference call discussing the Yahoo bid Friday, Microsoft CEO Steve Ballmer made a pointed reference to efforts to shed its desktop legacy and move even aspects of its Windows OS to the Web, a trend the company started with some features in the latest version, Windows Vista.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">&quot;The Windows user wants to be live, the Windows experience needs to increasingly embrace the Internet,&quot; he said. &quot;There will be a Windows Live, there will be an Office Live as we continue to bring out innovations in which Office transforms and is transformed by the Internet.&quot;</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">Ballmer also likely had the rising popularity of Web-hosted productivity software, such as Google Apps, Zoho, and&#160;<a href="http://www.infoworld.com/article/07/09/17/Yahoo-to-buy-Zimbra_1.html">Yahoo&#39;s Zimbra</a>, in mind when considering how to Web-enable Microsoft&#39;s desktop software. So far, Microsoft&#39;s Office Live has been more of a way for small businesses to get up and running with a Web site and basic hosted business applications&#160;such as&#160;accounting and CRM; however, bringing a full productivity suite to the Web has been Microsoft&#39;s plan for some time.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">Microsoft also can leverage its own strength among business customers to bundle and technically link applications so that customers buy an all-in-one package rather than individual products. For instance, Microsoft has created tight links between a new unified communications product, Office Communications Server, and its Office and SharePoint collaboration software so that customers must buy them all together to create comprehensive infrastructure. Microsoft can make similar attachments between online versions of its applications -- or just bundle them together in creative ways -- and market them to a broader audience.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">&quot;If Microsoft does something well, it&#39;s bundling products and services,&quot; said Ned May, director and lead analyst of marketing research firm Outsell. He joked that if Microsoft purchases Yahoo, there might come a day when you start up Windows and &quot;up pops Yahoo, and it takes you three days to remove that functionality.&quot;</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">&quot;Yahoo provides a platform in many regards -- an audience of 500 million people to which you can bundle products and new offerings,&quot; May said.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">Doing quick math, May figured that at &quot;500 million a month for about $44 billion,&quot; it will cost Microsoft about $86 a head for acquiring each member of its new audience of Web users. &quot;Not a bad deal,&quot; he said.</p></div>	4	2008-02-02 01:53:03	\N
InfoWorld news	http://www.infoworld.com/cgi-bin/redirect?source=rss&url=http://www.infoworld.com/article/08/02/01/Microsoft-bid-caps-turbulent-week_1.html	Microsoft bid caps turbulent week	none	Sci/Tech	<div class="rxbodyfield"><p page="1" class="ArticleBody"><a href="http://www.infoworld.com/archives/t.jsp?N=s&amp;V=95033">Microsoft&#39;s offer Friday to buy Yahoo</a>&#160;for $44.6 billion in cash and shares put a turbulent end to a heavy earnings week in which forecasts from Internet leaders worried IT investors.</p><p align="right"><a href="http://ad.doubleclick.net/jump/idg.us.info.rss/news;pos=imu;tile=6;sz=336x280;skey=patch_management;pkey=security;ord=123456789?" target="_blank" /><img src="http://ad.doubleclick.net/ad/idg.us.info.rss/news;pos=imu;tile=6;sz=336x280;skey=patch_management;pkey=security;ord=123456789?" width="336" height="280" border="0" alt="" align="right"/></a></p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">Internet leaders Google, Yahoo, and Amazon and a host of high-profile technology vendors this week reported fourth-quarter sales and generally muted forecasts for the next few quarters.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody"><a href="http://www.infoworld.com/article/08/02/01/Microsoft-offer-to-Yahoo-board_1.html">Microsoft CEO Steve Ballmer&#39;s offer letter to Yahoo&#39;s board of directors</a>&#160;on Thursday went public Friday morning, having an immediate effect on company share prices. The offer represents a 62 percent premium over Yahoo&#39;s closing price on Thursday. In premarket trading, Yahoo shares skyrocketed. Shares closed at $28.38, up by $9.20, or 47.97 percent.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">Though most analysts said the deal would not likely hurt Google in the short term, Google shares closed down by $48.40, at $515.90. Shares of Microsoft, which has never done a deal this size, were down by $2.15, closing at $30.45.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">Considering Yahoo&#39;s likely earnings and share price increases without an acquisition, for the price Microsoft is willing to pay, the offer &quot;seems like a great deal,&quot; said Citigroup analyst Mark Mahaney in a research note.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">The proposal capped off a heavy earnings-report week. Though sales for the fourth quarter generally were strong, key companies, including Google and high-flying virtualization technology vendor VMware, fell short of analyst expectations.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">In the current economic climate in the United States, where many analysts are predicting a recession, market watchers pounce on bad news.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody"><a href="http://www.infoworld.com/article/08/01/29/Yahoos-Q4-sales-up-profit-down_1.html">Yahoo&#39;s fourth-quarter revenue increased, but profit fell to $206 million</a>&#160;from $269 million one year earlier. During its financial conference call Wednesday, CEO Jerry Yang announced that the company would be laying off about 1,000 workers and talked about the U.S. economy hitting the company with &quot;headwinds.&quot;</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">Analysts worry that the company&#39;s Panama search engine ad system, rolled out last year, has not had the positive effect that was expected. They also note that the company is vague about expected investments and that it is appearing to lose further ground to Google in the search market.</p><p page="1" class="ArticleBody">In a research note, Citigroup Global Markets Equity Research downgraded its opinion on Yahoo from &quot;buy&quot; to &quot;hold.&quot; But after the Microsoft offer went public, Citigroup called the move &quot;a good fit to fix an ongoing issue.&quot;</p><p page="2" class="ArticleBody">Though&#160;<a href="http://www.infoworld.com/article/08/01/31/Google-earnings-up-shy-of-expectations_1.html?source=rss&amp;url=http://www.infoworld.com/article/08/01/31/Google-earnings-up-shy-of-expectations_1.html">Google on Thursday reported a 51 percent year-on-year revenue increase</a>&#160;to $4.83 billion for the quarter, earnings per share excluding certain items were $4.43, just below the $4.44 consensus analyst forecast. While most companies would be ecstatic to report such strong growth, the market had gotten used to Google continuing to blow past all expectations.</p><p page="2" class="ArticleBody">Many market watchers take Google&#39;s miss as a sign that the faltering economy is braking the search giant. If consumers cut back spending, Google may experience a slackening in consumers&#39; desire to click on advertising. The company&#39;s continuing reliance on search revenue is bothering investors. That issue may be worrying investors more than potential competition with a merged Microsoft-Yahoo.</p><p page="2" class="ArticleBody">One bright note for the week in the Internet sector was Amazon&#39;s earnings announcement on Wednesday. Amazon revenue grew 42 percent, to $5.67 billion, as income more than doubled, to $207 million. While the company&#39;s forecast for operating margins was lower than expected, its revenue forecast was higher than expected -- welcome news in a climate of worry.</p><p page="2" class="ArticleBody">Then on Thursday,&#160;<a href="http://www.infoworld.com/article/08/01/31/Amazon-buys-Audible-for-300-million_1.html">Amazon announced it would buy Audible.com</a> , which sparked interest as the acquisition may help its battle against Apple in the market for spoken-word books, magazines, and radio programs. Amazon shares jumped by $3.49 to close at $77.70 Thursday, though they then drifted back down Friday.</p><p page="2" class="ArticleBody">Outside the Internet arena, companies in a variety of sectors, including Lenovo, SAP, Verizon, and TSMC, reported strong fourth-quarter sales (though in SAP&#39;s case, profit was brought down by its acquisition of Business Objects). However, as usual in these times of economic uncertainty, it was&#160;<a href="http://weblog.infoworld.com/tech-bottom-line/archives/2008/01/ouch_vmware_dru.html">VMware&#39;s disappointing quarter and weak forecast</a> &#160;that captured the most attention.</p><p page="2" class="ArticleBody">The company share price lost 34 percent of its value after VMware said Monday that revenue was $412.5 million, compared to analyst expectations of $417.4 million. Even though profit doubled, it was the revenue miss that had everyone nervous as hopes for the company were high after its red-hot IPO in December.</p><p page="2" class="ArticleBody">&quot;The company&#39;s 2008 outlook suggests that low hanging fruit may have been picked and new customer signings could be slowing down,&quot; according to a UBS research note. This comment is probably right on the money. Most big-company CIOs consider server virtualization an obvious tactical move and have already implemented the technology.</p><p page="2" class="ArticleBody">By market close Friday, excitement over the Microsoft offer for Yahoo may have helped push the tech-heavy Nasdaq Composite Index into positive territory. It closed at 2413.36, up by 23.50. As economic uncertainty rules, however, IT investors are bracing for a bumpy ride over the next few quarters.</p></div>	4	2008-02-02 03:33:02	\N

Scripting News	http://www.scripting.com/stories/2008/02/01/blogsWinTheLongnowBet.html	Blogs win the LongNow bet	none	Software and Developement	Decision: <a href="http://blog.longnow.org/2008/02/01/decision-blogs-vs-new-york-times/">Blogs vs. New York Times</a>.<br><br>\
For the last couple of weeks I've been emailing with people from the LongNow Foundation and Martin Nisenholtz of the NY Times, to determine who won the bet. <br><br>\
Ultimately we asked the foundation to consider all the argument and make the decision.<br><br>\
They published their decision today. It's well worth reading because it answers some of the questions raised by the bet, for example, what is a blog, and how does Wikipedia relate to blogging. I don't agree with everything in the decision, but I do like the result -- we won. <img src="http://www.scripting.com/gifs/QBullets/qbullets/sidesmiley.gif" width="11" height="11" border="0" alt="smile"><br><br>\
The beneficiary of the bet? <a href="http://www.w3.org/">The World Wide Web Consortium</a>. I chose them as the charity to receive the proceeds if I won the bet because web standards are what make it all work and the W3C is central to standards on the web.<br><br>\

Scripting News	http://www.scripting.com/stories/2008/02/01/bestFeelgoodPictureOf2007.html	Best feel-good picture of 2007	none	Software and Developement	Okay, a few days ago I wrote a <a href="http://www.scripting.com/stories/2008/01/26/everybodysDivingBell.html">review</a> of the Diving Bell and the Butterfly saying it could be the best picture of 2007, but even so you might want to skip it because the truth it reveals might be something you don't want to look at. It's a fine picture, but a tough one.<br><br>\
Another wonderful but tough picture is <a href="http://www.google.com/movies/reviews?cid=b8c422007696297f&fq=No+Country+for+Old+Men&sa=X&oi=showtimes&ct=reviews&cd=1">No Country for Old Men</a>. It's one of those movies that leaves so much unresolved that you walk out of the theater not sure which foot goes in front of the other. On a second viewing it makes much more sense. The world isn't necessarily as crazy as it at first seemed.<br><br>\
<a href="http://images.scripting.com/archiveScriptingCom/2008/02/01/junoWithPipeInChair.jpg"><img src="http://images.scripting.com/archiveScriptingCom/2008/02/01/juno.jpg" width="83" height="114" border="0" align="right" hspace="15" vspace="5" alt="A picture named juno.jpg"></a>But there's a movie that is also incredibly well crafted, and gets better every time you think about it -- <a href="http://www.google.com/movies/reviews?cid=be72a38733bef9bd&fq=Juno">Juno</a>. I didn't realize how much I liked it until I heard someone compare it to Little Miss Sunshine, a movie that I did not enjoy, unlike everyone else it seems. I <i>loved</i> Juno because it organizes its sweetness into love for one person, the star of the movie, Juno. But everyone, no matter how dorky or clueless (and some of the adults are <i>truly</i> dorky and clueless) shares the love. The movie has a wholeness, an unqualified goodness, you not only walk out of the theater in love with Juno and everyone else in the movie, but your heart is warmed for everyone, including yourself. It's <i>that</i> good. <br><br>\
All three remind how good movies can be.<br><br>\
And there were some not-too-bad movies at the end of 2007, for example, <a href="http://www.google.com/movies/reviews?cid=b961e568572dc490&fq=Atonement">Atonement</a>, which some didn't like, but I did. <a href="http://www.google.com/movies/reviews?cid=b341b9de30507f2f&fq=3:10+to+Yuma">3:10 to Yuma</a> is a well-crafted genre picture. <a href="http://www.google.com/movies/reviews?cid=bc70be450fa121fa&fq=Michael+Clayton">Michael Clayton</a> was a perfect showcase for the talents of George Clooney. Great acting and a simple story in <a href="http://www.google.com/movies/reviews?cid=b7d197d583f2ed1f&fq=The+Savages">The Savages</a>. <br><br>\
Which one was the best? I'd hate to have to choose!<br><br>\

<p>Google invited developers to its London office for one of three workshops - the others being in Munich and Tel Aviv to spread the word and teach developers how to write for their new OS. Another event will be held in Boston on February 23rd (check at <a href="http://android-developers.blogspot.com/" target="_blank">the blog</a> for an announcement). Here's what they told us. The mantra for Android is that it’s "a complete and modern embedded OS, with a cutting edge mobile user experience, a world class software stack for building apps and open platform for developers users and industry". That of course breaks into lots of different specifics some of which are more solid than others. Computer people coming to mobile have a very different view of phone architecture to phone people adding features. Phone people see the phone functions - the GSM chipset, Bluetooth, DVB-H, for example, as a foundation, with drivers on top. The Register	http://go.theregister.com/feed/www.regdeveloper.co.uk/2008/02/02/google_android_developers_view/	Google Android - a sneak preview	http___regmedia.co.uk_2007_07_04_email_symbol_75.jpg.gif	Sci/Tech	<h4>What's in it for developers?</h4>\
<p>Google invited developers to its London office for one of three workshops - the others being in Munich and Tel Aviv to spread the word and teach developers how to write for their new OS. Another event will be held in Boston on February 23rd (check at <a href="http://android-developers.blogspot.com/" target="_blank">the blog</a> for an announcement). Here's what they told us. The mantra for Android is that it’s "a complete and modern embedded OS, with a cutting edge mobile user experience, a world class software stack for building apps and open platform for developers users and industry". That of course breaks into lots of different specifics some of which are more solid than others. Computer people coming to mobile have a very different view of phone architecture to phone people adding features. Phone people see the phone functions - the GSM chipset, Bluetooth, DVB-H, for example, as a foundation, with drivers on top. Then there's an abstraction layer, an operating system, a user interface framework and the applications on top.…</p>	5	2008-02-02 07:01:33	\N

InfoWorld news	http://www.infoworld.com/cgi-bin/redirect?source=rss&url=http://www.infoworld.com/article/08/02/02/news-microsoft-yahoo-it_1.html	Microsoft's Yahoo bid is really about business apps	none	Sci/Tech	<div class="rxbodyfield"><p class="ArticleBody" page="1">At first blush, Microsoft's <a href="http://www.infoworld.com/article/08/02/01/Microsoft-offers-to-buy-Yahoo-for-44-billion_1.html" class="regularArticleU">proposed acquisition</a> of Yahoo for $46.6 billion is about growing its consumer advertising and portal business to better compete wit Google. And that's certainly part of the mix, but perhaps lost in the discussion is how such an acquisition could help Microsoft execute its software-plus-services strategy for delivering business apps over the Internet faster and better, said several analysts. That strategy could help Microsoft compete with Google's own business-apps initiative, they said.</p><p align="right"><a href="http://ad.doubleclick.net/jump/idg.us.info.rss/news;pos=imu;tile=6;sz=336x280;skey=patch_management;pkey=security;ord=123456789?" target="_blank" /><img src="http://ad.doubleclick.net/ad/idg.us.info.rss/news;pos=imu;tile=6;sz=336x280;skey=patch_management;pkey=security;ord=123456789?" width="336" height="280" border="0" alt="" align="right"/></a></p><p class="ArticleBody" page="1"><b>[ Follow</b> <b><a href="http://www.infoworld.com/archives/t.jsp?N=s&amp;V=95033" class="regularArticleU">InfoWorld's ongoing coverage</a> of Microsoft's offer to buy Yahoo ]</b></p><p class="ArticleBody" page="1">"Yahoo has very efficient datacenters, as does Microsoft," noted Rob Koplowitz, a Forrester Research analyst. By combining their datacenters -- and, more important, their engineering talent -- Microsoft should be able to move faster and more efficiently on delivering business apps over the Internet, something that Microsoft has done at a fairly slow pace so far. "Yahoo's engineers can help," he noted, "And you know that there'll be engineers who are freed up" after the acquisition, <a href="http://www.infoworld.com/video/News/Microsoft-Yahoo/Microsoft-Yahoo-analysis/video_2178.html" class="regularArticleU">should it go through</a>.</p><p class="ArticleBody" page="1">"Although Google Applications have yet to make a real dent in the Microsoft Office giant, they do pose a long-term threat," said David Mitchell, a senior IT researcher at the consultancy Ovum. "As a defense against this position, Microsoft needs to accelerate its own move into online services. The online engineering capabilities that Yahoo has will undoubtedly offer Microsoft the potential to bring new services to market" and will help Microsoft stay competitive.</p><p class="ArticleBody" page="1">Koplowitz said he does not believe Microsoft is trying to buy specific technology from Yahoo to fill a hole needed to compete against Google's business offerings. Microsoft wants more talent and capacity to follow its existing strategy, he said. Google's approach is to offer pure Web-based apps, which he noted are more mature than Microsoft's Web-delivered apps. Microsoft's approach is to extend its 450 million Office desktop seats through additional software delivered via the Internet. The strategies have some overlap, but because they are different, Koplowitz expects Microsoft and Google to take different technology paths rather than try to copy each other.</p><p class="ArticleBody" page="1">Microsoft's acquisition of Yahoo would also bolster the company in another area where it has fallen behind Google: search, said Charlene Yi, a Forrester analyst. "Microsoft is interested in search because it provides a beachhead into businesses -- especially small and medium-sized ones that don't have a direct relationship with Microsoft," she said, as businesses typically buy Office software from retailers and resellers. Google is using search to forge those direct relationships and then offer business apps that compete with Microsoft's plans.</p></div>	4	2008-02-02 13:22:18	\N
